# A8-f40b-sysfs-observability — per-PCI-device sysfs surface for F40b state + counters.
#
# Adds 5 read-only sysfs attributes under each nvidia-bound PCI device:
#
#   tb_egpu_state              healthy | recovering | lost-temporary | lost-permanent
#   tb_egpu_f40b_fires         counter of F40b timeout fires since last bind (A6 + A7)
#   tb_egpu_recovery_count     counter of successful recoveries (set by A9)
#   tb_egpu_recovery_failures  counter of failed recoveries (set by A9)
#   tb_egpu_last_recovery_ns   ktime_get_ns() of last successful recovery (set by A9)
#
# === v2: sysfs_create_group, NOT pci_driver.driver.dev_groups ===
#
# A8 v1 registered the attribute group via nv_pci_driver.driver.dev_groups.
# It compiled and every symbol loaded (dev_attr_tb_egpu_* visible in
# /proc/kallsyms), but produced ZERO sysfs paths at runtime.  Root cause:
# __pci_register_driver() executes
#
#     drv->driver.dev_groups = drv->dev_groups;
#
# (drivers/pci/pci-driver.c) — clobbering the inner .driver.dev_groups field
# v1 set with the NULL *outer* pci_driver.dev_groups.  Verified empirically on
# aorus.19 (attrs absent), then fixed + verified live on aorus.20 (all 5
# attrs materialise at /sys/bus/pci/devices/<bdf>/).
#
# v2 mirrors the proven addon A2 (Q-watchdog) / A3 (recovery) idiom: explicit
# sysfs_create_group on &nvl->pci_dev->dev.kobj at probe, sysfs_remove_group at
# remove, with the A3 fail-soft policy (NV_DBG_INFO log, if(nvl->pci_dev) guard,
# non-fatal so the driver binds regardless).
#
# Implementation:
#   - New TU nv-tb-egpu-metrics.{c,h} (relocated from the v1 nv.c inline block,
#     mirroring A1/A2/A3 file geometry: new .c + .h + nvidia-sources.Kbuild line).
#   - tb_egpu_metrics_init(nvl) wired into nv_pci_probe after tb_egpu_qwd_init.
#   - tb_egpu_metrics_stop(nvl) wired into nv_pci_remove_helper before
#     tb_egpu_qwd_stop.
#
# F40b fire hooks (nv.c) — two variants, so the counter covers both paths while
# state transitions only on a genuine usability failure:
#   - nv_tb_egpu_f40b_fired()           A6 OPEN path: f40b_fires++ AND
#     state -> lost-temporary.  An open that times out means the GPU failed to
#     come up — it is genuinely unusable.
#   - nv_tb_egpu_f40b_fired_teardown()  A7 SHUTDOWN path: f40b_fires++ ONLY.
#     rm_shutdown_adapter times out structurally on every healthy teardown (A7
#     Test A), including the pre-persistence close-path fire during bring-up.
#     That is a teardown artifact, not a "GPU is now unusable" event, so it must
#     NOT strand tb_egpu_state at lost-temporary (which would read lost-temporary
#     on a demonstrably healthy GPU after every normal bring-up, with no path
#     back to healthy until A9).  Counting it honours A7's "single counter for
#     both A6 and A7 fires" contract; not transitioning state keeps the health
#     signal truthful.  (This split is the v2.1 fix found in the live aorus.20
#     deploy: a single counter+state hook left a healthy GPU reading
#     lost-temporary.)
#   - The v1 dev_groups field on nv_pci_driver and the nv_tb_egpu_dev_groups[]
#     wrapper are gone.
#
# Reset-on-bind: tb_egpu_metrics_init calls nv_tb_egpu_metrics_reset() before
# publishing the group, zeroing counters + state=healthy each bind generation.
# The metrics struct is module-static single-instance (single-eGPU posture), so
# without this an unbind-rebind (DaemonSet pod restart) would re-expose stale
# counters from the prior bind.  Verified live on aorus.20 (f40b_fires read 1,
# not an accumulation, after one bring-up fire).
#
# Dependencies: A6 (open-path hook site) + A7 (shutdown-path hook site).
# Single-GPU assumption: module-global metrics; refactor to per-device storage
# via nv_linux_state_t when multi-GPU support is needed.
#
# Telemetry tier: nominal (machine-readable state + counters; no kernel-log
# emission — that is A6/A7's job, and A9's for the recovery state machine).
#
# Adversarially reviewed 2026-05-30 (4-lens workflow + per-finding verify) and
# live-validated on aorus.20: no use-after-free (module-static metrics; group
# removed before any teardown), reset-vs-reader race safe (kernfs active-ref
# draining), atomic types consistent, sysfs_emit buffer-safe.
#
# Author: nvidia-driver-injector contributors
# Date:   2026-05-30
# License: MIT

